Most of us who develop for opensource projects do so in our free time, and we have day jobs to pay the bills. Some are lucky enough to work for companies that are sympathetic towards opensource software and encourage their developers to contribute to OS repositories; other companies give absolutely no freedom to develop for OS projects during working hours, and some are hostile towards OS development and may even clain that they own all code that a developer writes, even outside working hours.

This can impact the enjoyment and productivity of opensource developers; it's obviously easier and more rewarding to do it while working a day job for a company that looks favorably towards it, partly because such companies tend to attract similar-minded developers who can make such work more rewarding and encourage a learning environment.

This survey didn't take all of this into account, and I think some questions about our day jobs and how well they mix with our opensource development would be illuminating.
